# Imagery

A picture earns its bandwidth. Before shipping any image, it must answer **yes to at least two** of: *Is it relevant? Is it interesting? Is it appealing?*

## Choosing Images

- **Relevant** but boring is often worse than *interesting* and tangential. Avoid the literal cliché (the "happy headset call-center woman", the smiling stock office team).
- **Direction matters.** A subject facing inward draws the eye into the content; facing outward, the eye leaves the page. Crop and place so visual lines flow toward the next focal point.
- Photos of recognizable people require model releases. Photos of products/logos/celebrities require licensing.

## Legitimate Sources

- **Own work** — take/draw it yourself when feasible. Even simple, single-color illustrations can be effective.
- **Stock** — three tiers:
  - *Free*: Unsplash, Pexels, Stock.XCHNG, public-domain archives. Quality varies; always check the license.
  - *Royalty-free*: iStock, Dreamstime, Shutterstock — pay once, reuse forever.
  - *Rights-managed*: Getty, Corbis — exclusivity for a price.
- **Commission** a photographer/illustrator when budget allows and the work is core to the brand.

## Never Do These

- **Google ganking** — saving images from search results and using them without license. Risk: takedowns, lawsuits.
- **Hotlinking** — `<img src="https://someone-else.com/image.jpg">`. Steals bandwidth, breaks when they rename. Always host or proxy.
- **Generic clipart and corny animated GIFs** in professional work.
- **Flickr CC without attribution** — at minimum, link credit to the photographer.

## Cropping and Composition

- Crop ruthlessly. Remove distractions (foreground clutter, power lines, half-cropped people).
- Use the **rule of thirds** for placement of the subject; don't always center.
- Try unconventional masks: text as a clip, organic shapes (`clip-path`), gradient/duotone overlays. Done well these are striking; done badly they look amateur — test at the final size.

## Adjustments

- Match the image's color cast to the site's palette (subtle duotone or color overlay can rescue mismatched stock).
- Maintain consistent treatment across all images on the page — same crop ratios, same filters, same border radius.
- Verify quality at the largest size the image will display. Don't enlarge low-res sources; cropped grain is more forgiving than upscaling blur.

## File Formats — Pick the Right One

| Use case | Format | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Photos | **AVIF** preferred, **WebP** fallback, JPG legacy | Use `<picture>` for format negotiation |
| Logos, icons, illustrations | **SVG** | Inline for theming/animation; cache external for repeated assets |
| UI icons (set) | **SVG sprite** or icon font | Avoid icon fonts for new work — SVG is more accessible |
| Screenshots, line art with transparency | **PNG** (or WebP) | Use `image-rendering: pixelated` only for intentional retro |
| Short animation | **WebM/MP4** with `<video autoplay muted playsinline loop>` | Never animated GIF for long clips |

- Always set explicit `width` and `height` attributes (or aspect-ratio in CSS) to prevent layout shift (CLS).
- Always provide meaningful `alt` text — empty `alt=""` only for purely decorative images.
- Use `loading="lazy"` for below-the-fold images and `fetchpriority="high"` for the LCP image.
- Serve responsive sizes via `srcset` + `sizes`; don't ship 3000px images to phones.

## Enhance with CSS, Not Photoshop

CSS filters, blend modes, `clip-path`, gradients, and `mask-image` can recreate most "Photoshop effects" without baking them into the asset — keeping images theme-able and lightweight.

## Quick Checks

1. Does this image answer yes to at least two of relevant/interesting/appealing?
2. Is it licensed for this use, and is the source documented?
3. Does the subject face *into* the content, not away from it?
4. Is the image served in a modern format at responsive sizes with `alt`, `width`, and `height`?
5. Does it share crop ratio, color treatment, and styling with the other images on the page?
